# Platform Profile: Meta AI / Llama

**Provider:** Meta  
**Current Models:** Llama 4 (Scout, Maverick, Behemoth)  
**Interface:** meta.ai (consumer), API via Meta or third-party providers, self-hosted open weights

---

## Strengths
- Fully open-weight: download model weights, run anywhere, no API dependency
- Complete data sovereignty — nothing leaves your infrastructure
- Fine-tunable on proprietary data with full control over training
- Closing the gap with proprietary frontier models on many benchmarks
- Meta AI (consumer): integrated into WhatsApp, Instagram, Facebook, Messenger
- Llama 4 Scout: 10M token context window (experimental)
- Cost elimination at scale: run at marginal compute cost once deployed
- Strong community ecosystem: thousands of fine-tuned variants available
- Air-gapped deployment: fully offline, no internet required

## Weaknesses
- Self-hosted requires significant infrastructure investment and expertise
- Base models require fine-tuning or careful prompting to match frontier model quality
- Consumer Meta AI interface is social-context-first — not suited for professional/enterprise tasks
- No managed enterprise product with the maturity of ChatGPT Enterprise or M365 Copilot
- Model updates require re-downloading and re-deploying weights

## Context Window
- Llama 4 Scout: up to 10M tokens (experimental)
- Llama 4 Maverick: 1M tokens
- Behavior: context window is large but quality at extreme lengths depends on deployment configuration

## Memory & Persistence
- **Self-hosted:** Full control — implement any memory architecture (vector DB, RAG, session state)
- **Fine-tuned models:** Behavioral preferences baked into weights
- **Consumer Meta AI:** Limited persistence within social app context
- **Handoff note:** For professional use, always target self-hosted or third-party API deployments, not consumer Meta AI

## System Prompt Support
- ✅ Self-hosted: full system prompt control
- ✅ Third-party API providers (Together AI, Groq, Fireworks): full system prompt support
- ⚠️ Consumer Meta AI: limited system prompt access

## Tool Availability
- Self-hosted: any tool integrable via custom implementation
- Third-party APIs: varies by provider (search, code execution available on some)
- Consumer Meta AI: web search, image generation
- No native enterprise tool suite

## Prompt Format Conventions
- Base Llama models: use chat template format specific to the model version
- Fine-tuned models: follow the instruction format used during fine-tuning
- Self-hosted: system prompt is your primary control surface
- For third-party APIs: follows standard OpenAI-compatible API conventions
- Llama 4 Instruct: direct task instructions work well; structured prompts improve consistency

## Ideal Task Types
- Air-gapped / offline deployments (defense, healthcare, finance with strict data controls)
- Fine-tuning on proprietary domain data (legal, medical, financial, internal knowledge bases)
- High-volume inference where cloud API cost is prohibitive
- Privacy-sensitive work requiring zero data egress
- Research and experimentation with model behavior
- Building custom AI products without model licensing restrictions
- Multilingual applications (Llama 4 has broad language coverage)

